## 1. Introduction

Emotional text-to-speech (TTS) aims to generate speech from text that conveys human-like emotions [1]. Recent advances in deep learning have significantly enhanced its capabilities. As a pivotal technology for human-computer interaction, emotional TTS facilitates the development of dialogue systems that are both engaging and empathetic [2].

However, current emotional TTS systems face challenges stemming from the complexity of human emotions and the limited range of emotional labels available in existing databases [2]. Psychological research suggests that humans can experience around 34,000 distinct emotions [3], yet current systems struggle to capture this full spectrum. Previous emotional TTS studies have primarily relied on two approaches: supervision using categorical emotion labels $[4,5]$ and style transfer from reference speech $[6,7]$. Both approaches are constrained by the limited diversity of emotional styles present in available datasets, often resulting in synthesized speech with averaged or stereotypical emotional expressions, which restricts fine-grained control over emotion rendering $[8,9]$.

Recent language model (LM)-based TTS frameworks [10, 11] show strong in-context learning capabilities. With sufficient training data, these models effectively render appropriate prosody for complex text inputs and exhibit robust zero-shot speaker cloning capabilities. Unlike traditional TTS task, which focus primarily on capturing a wide range of phonetic variations across speakers [12], emotional TTS emphasizes rendering diverse emotional styles, thus requiring large and varied emotional speech datasets with detailed emotion annotations. Emo-
tional TTS systems like CosyVoice [13] and EmoCtrl-TTS [14], built on state-of-the-art language models, require thousands of hours of emotional speech data, highlighting the complexity and cost of data collection. However, publicly available emotional speech datasets are typically small [15], making them inadequate for training robust LM-based TTS system from scratch. A common strategy is to fine-tune a pre-trained TTS model using small emotional datasets [16], but this approach risks overfitting and limits generalization across emotions and speakers [17]. To address these limitations, we propose a novel framework that synthesizes more nuanced and subtle emotions not present in the dataset by controlling continuous emotional dimensions. This method offers greater flexibility for emotion rendering and leverages the in-context learning capabilities of language models, enabling the generation of a wide spectrum of human emotions, even with limited or no emotion-labeled data.

In this paper, we propose an effective approach for LMbased TTS systems to generate diverse emotional styles by controlling an emotional dimension vector. Our method draws inspiration from Russell's emotion theory [18], which identifies three independent dimensions-pleasure, arousal, and domi-nance-as sufficient to capture the complexity of emotional expressions across various contexts and individuals. Using these dimensions as foundational anchors, we develop a model that predicts their values. The pre-trained dimension predictor is then integrated into a LM-based TTS system to assist in nexttoken prediction, alongside the speaker embedding. During inference, our framework enables direct control over emotional dimensions, allowing the synthesis of diverse emotional styles without requiring emotional reference inputs. Our contributions are summarize as below:

- We introduce a novel approach for controlling emotional dimensions in language model-based TTS systems, enabling fine-grained emotional speech synthesis;
- Our approach learns emotional styles directly from expressive speech, eliminating the need for explicit emotion labels during TTS training;
- During inference, the model allows users to control and explore a broad spectrum of human emotions by adjusting the emotional dimension vector. Grounded in established psychological theory, this approach ensures that the synthesized emotional styles align with the full range of human emotions;
- We further demonstrate that our method enhances naturalness in zero-shot speaker cloning tasks, consistently outperforming the baseline system;

We introduce our proposed method in Section 2. In Section 3, we report our experimental results. Section 4 concludes the paper.

